column1: Before 17 August 2019, will retirement savings legislation known as the SECURE Act become law?
column6: ['Economic Policy', 'US Politics', 'US Policy']

I have a high level of confidence that it will pass at some point (strong bipartisan support, House wants to pushed through quickly), but doesn't seem likely to pass by Aug 17 given the hold up in the Senate due to the removal in the House version of provisions that would have allowed funds in 529 college savings plans to be used for home schooling costs and supplies for K-12 students, among other objections. Given the 17th is fast approaching I'm not sure they'll be able to overcome the objections raised by certain Senators.

Post mortem lesson: * I was overly optimistic based on passage in the House which led me to discount base rates for just how few bills become law, and within a short period like this no less. Takeaway - this is a good reminder that passage in the Senate is often more difficult. After all, the Senate was designed to be a more stable institution than the House, more conservative, and more resistant to change, be the bulwark against the vicissitudes of popular opinion, "the saucer that cools the tea" as Washington called it. * I was overly optimistic because I believe the bill to have bipartisan appeal and be uncontroversial. Takeaway - another good reminder that large pieces of legislation have plenty of provisions that can run individual senators the wrong way (e.g. homeschooling funding in this bill) * The procedure of unanimous consent in the Senate is a high bar to clear

The retirement reform bill SECURE Act was passed by the House on May 23 by a large margin of 417-3. The Senate has its own retirement reform bill called RESA. Normally the two versions will have to go through a long process of reconciliation to work out their differences. However, the Senate decided to forgo this length process. Instead it opted for the "unanimous consent" approach in which the bill will be passed in the Senate if everybody agrees. This would have speed up the passing of the bill significantly. However, Ted Cruz objected (placed a hold on the bill) due to his disagreement with the 529 plan in the SECURE Act.

The US Senate is only in session the last 3 weeks in July and the first few days in August. So I think there will be more adjustments to the bill during that time that will delay the ultimate passage of the law.

Unless The Current Incumbent comes out strongly for this quite soon, the calendar is not on their side. It would sort of surprise me if it didn't pass some time after 17 August, but even with strong bipartisan support, this is a tight deadline in the current climate--and also in the current weather, what with summer vacations coming up for the poor exhausted Members.
Historically, 10% of bills become laws [1]. Yet, this is in a different reference case since the bill has already passed the House with a large bipartisan majority.

This is an excellent piece of legislation with strong bipartisan support. Ordinarily this would doom it, but the Orange House hasn't yet pronounced on it. If The Current Incumbent comes out strongly for it soon and doesn't Twit out a reversal within, say, 48 hours, it should actually be enacted. If he doesn't come out strongly for it, Distinguished Majority Leader Yertle the Turtle (R-Ky) will continue pretending to be dead and let it languish. And of course if The Current Incumbent notices that it will help some people who can't do him much good, he may decide to oppose it. Interesting times, in a train-wreck sort of a way.
